  "articleSummary": "This 2015 reference guide argues that Docker enables developers to rapidly provision isolated, disposable database environments, effectively eliminating legacy dependency conflicts and cross-project data contamination. Targeted at developers managing sensitive client work, inherited codebases, or outdated software requirements, the article adopts a direct, tutorial-style tone focused on immediate, actionable setup. It provides one-line commands to launch popular databases like PostgreSQL and MySQL, framing containerization as a clean \"throw-away\" workflow that strictly controls data persistence. While the author explicitly notes that modern practices like Docker Compose, pinned image versions, and secret management now offer safer defaults, the piece remains a practical local-development reference for quick database isolation.",
